Hi Geoff - at the start of this, on the platform of Bond Street, there's a door behind you on the opposite side of the tunnel from the platform, the floor of which is couple of inches above the height of the rails and below platform level. What on Earth is that doing there?!


I seem to remember they only crop up at a few platforms on the westbound branch of the Central Line between Bond Street and perhaps Holland Park? I've puzzled over them before, but no one seems to see them or know what they're for. Any ideas?

snippet.textDisplay:
This series of videos underlines that in zone 1 and zone 2, as well as perhaps some examples elsewhere, some knowledge of the geography and transport links (or these days, if you don't have that local knowledge, using the Citymapper app) helps rather than blindly assuming the Tube will always be quicker.


I knew that both the journeys featured in this video are quicker to walk as I am familiar with the Bayswater and Paddington area. As Vicki found, it is easy to miss the most direct route between Lancaster Gate and Paddington stations.



In my student days in London, I often heard tourists insisting they were going to go between Marble Arch and Hyde Park Corner (or vice versa) using the Underground. There is no quick way to do this journey by Underground: Central Line to Holborn and Piccadilly Line to Hyde Park Corner is about as quick as it gets. It is far faster to take a bus down Park Lane. Indeed, it is likely quicker to walk than take the Underground.
